Some crosstalk simulations

The following simulations were performed with the "large" feed that has a flat ~50% efficiency across the band. This feed sticks out exactly 218 mm (this is the position at which it reaches that good efficiency).

Also note that unless indicated otherwise, these simulations were run without a balun. I will add a separate set of simulations for crosstalk with balun further down.

Adding a "sleeve" (or "fence")

I first simulate that setup in a simple 6 m dish with rim-to-rim distances of 10, 20, 40, and 80 cm. I then simulate the exact same thing, but adding a cylindrical "sleeve" that starts at the edge of the dish and goes up 218 mm (the distance by which the feed sticks out).

These two simulations are presented below. Note that I only present S1,3 (=S3,1) because these are the only S-parameters that are not negligibly small in these simulations (apart from S1,1, S2,2, S3,3, and S4,4). Ports 1 and 3 are each in a different dish, and their polarization plane is that in which the dish translation vector lie, i.e. the ground planes would eventually overlap if we were to extend them (ports 2 and 4 excite the planes that never overlap, that are orthogonal to the dish translation vector).

Also, the simulations are performed without a balun. Adding the baluns makes the S1,2 (=S2,1=S3,4=S4,3) go up to -35 dB at high frequencies, I will present that further down.

No sleeve, feed sticking out:
With sleeve that goes as high as the feed is sticking out:

Comment: we save ~5-10 dB in the most problematic part of the band (300-800 MHz) by adding the sleeves.

Making the dishes larger and deeper

I then simulate larger dishes, i.e. leaving the feed at the same location but continuing the parabola. I tried increasing the dish height by 10, 20, 40, and 80 cm, without keeping the diameter fixed (so effectively the focal ratio decreased). Here are the corresponding diameters:

Added depth (mm) Total depth (mm) Corresponding diameter (mm)
0 1500 6000
100 1600 6197
200 1700 6387
400 1900 6753
800 2300 7430

Note that the feed is always sticking out 218 mm above the focus (which is at 1500 mm from the bottom of the dish), so, for instance, in the "200 mm added depth" case, the feed is just sticking out 18 mm.

I run the simulations with a constant rim-to-rim distance of 400 mm, and compare the results with the two cases presented above (simple 6 m dish, 6 m dish with fence) at the same distances:
